Roman Shipwrecks network

Antonio Rivero Ostoic

CEDHAR, Aarhus University

jaro@cas.au.dk

20 januar 2022

This post concerns the Strauss shipwrecks database on Roman Shipwrecks network:

Strauss, J. (2013). Shipwrecks Database. Version 1.0. Accessed (07-12-2021) from oxrep.classics.ox.ac.uk/databases/shipwrecks_database/

Requirements

To run the code snippets below, we need the following R packages

# v0.7.4 or higher
library("sdam") 
library("readxl")
# v2.9.7 or higher
library("multiplex")
library("multigraph")

Shipwrecks database

Andrew Wilson coordinates a catalogue of all known ancient wrecks in the Mediterranean up to 1500 AD where there is the database from Julia Strausss PhD thesis Roman Cargoes: Underwater Evidence from the East (London 2007).

Retrieving the data

The Shipwrecks Database is distributed as a ZIP filesystem that needs a temporal file where to download it. The workflow below gives the steps in R with credits to this discussion.

temp <- tempfile()
download.file("http://oxrep.classics.ox.ac.uk/docs/StraussShipwrecks.zip", temp)

Next, we make the connection with the temporal file and unzip it with the "utils" package into object con, and because StraussShipwrecks is an MS Excel file with different sheets, we use package "readxl" to recursively read the excel sheets.

# connect temporal file and unzip excel file
con <- utils::unzip(temp, "StraussShipwrecks.xlsx")
# recursively read Excel sheets
allsheets <- sapply(readxl::excel_sheets(con), simplify=FALSE, USE.NAMES=TRUE,
            function(z) readxl::read_excel(con, sheet = z))

Before continuing with the analysis, however, we need to close the connections and remove unused files.

# close connection and garbage collection
CatchupPause <- function(Secs){
 Sys.sleep(Secs) # pause to let connection work
 closeAllConnections()
 gc()
}

# close also with temporal file
unlink(temp)

Analysis

We look at this database with the "base" summary() function.

# content in the excel sheets
summary(allsheets)
           Length Class  Mode
Shipwrecks 35     tbl_df list
Amphorae    5     tbl_df list

Where we can see that actually the database contains two datasets, Shipwrecks and Amphorae, which are components having 35 and 5 variables, respectively. We also notice that package "readxl" stores these data frames with a tibble flavour.

The first component of the database has the shipwrecks dataset recorded in sw where the variables are listed in the column names.

# shipwrecks dataset
sw <- allsheets$Shipwrecks

Timespans of existence

Use function plot.dates() from package "sdam" to plot the timespans of existence of the shipwrecks that are in variables 'Earliest date' and 'Latest date'.

# plot shipwrecks timespans
sdam::plot.dates(sw, taq="Earliest date", tpq="Latest date")

Shipwrecks timespans of existence

Alternatively, plot with plot.dates() using the two IDs existing in the dataset, which are Wreck ID and Strauss ID.

# use Wreck ID
plot.dates(sw, id="Wreck ID", 
           taq="Earliest date", tpq="Latest date")

# use Strauss ID
plot.dates(sw, id="Strauss ID", 
           taq="Earliest date", tpq="Latest date")

Sea areas

The shipwrecks dataset has geographical information to produce networks of relations with possible trajectories of the Roman ships. These variables are the Sea area of the shipwreck together with the network data in Place of origin and Place of destination that are columns 5, 20 and 21 in object sw.

sw[ ,c(5,20:21)]
# A tibble: 1,784 x 3

There are, however, that some record entries need cleaning from question marks, spaces, lower/upper cases, etc. Below, we look at some examples in the dataset, and use functionalities in the "sdam" internal function cln() that removes special characters and capitalizes words to uniform the data as much as possible for further analyses.

# four entries to clean
sw[c(6,9,35,130), c(5,20:21)]
# A tibble: 4 x 3
  `Sea area`            `Place of origin` `Place of destination`       
  <chr>                 <chr>             <chr>                        
1 Adriatic              Rhodes            northern Italy               
2 Tyrrhenian Sea        Aegean.           Rome                         
3 Aegean                Cos?              Black Sea?                   
4 Eastern Mediterranean Tripolitania (?)  Brega, for trans shipment (?)
# default clean
cln(sw[c(6,9,35,130), c(5,20:21)])
               Sea area Place of origin         Place of destination
1              Adriatic          Rhodes               northern Italy
2        Tyrrhenian Sea         Aegean.                         Rome
3                Aegean             Cos                    Black Sea
4 Eastern Mediterranean Tripolitania () Brega, for trans shipment ()
# include specific characters
cln(sw[c(6,9,35,130), c(5,20:21)], what=c("(",")"))
               Sea area Place of origin       Place of destination
1              Adriatic          Rhodes             northern Italy
2        Tyrrhenian Sea         Aegean.                       Rome
3                Aegean             Cos                  Black Sea
4 Eastern Mediterranean   Tripolitania  Brega, for trans shipment 
# raise level for dots and spaces at the end
cln(sw[c(6,9,35,130), c(5,20:21)], level=2, what=c("(",")"))
               Sea area Place of origin      Place of destination
1              Adriatic          Rhodes            northern Italy
2        Tyrrhenian Sea          Aegean                      Rome
3                Aegean             Cos                 Black Sea
4 Eastern Mediterranean    Tripolitania Brega, for trans shipment
# also capitalize words
cln(sw[c(6,9,35,130), c(5,20:21)], level=2, what=c("(",")"), case=1)
               Sea area Place of origin      Place of destination
1              Adriatic          Rhodes            Northern Italy
2        Tyrrhenian Sea          Aegean                      Rome
3                Aegean             Cos                 Black Sea
4 Eastern Mediterranean    Tripolitania Brega, For Trans Shipment

The first option removes only characters ?*+, and the second one removes also parenthesis. The command with a raised "level" removes also unnecessary spaces and dots at the end of each record, and 1 in "case" implies capitalization of just the first letter in each word.

Network relations

The places of origin and destination recorded in the Strauss shipwrecks dataset allows us producing a network representation of the possible trajectories of the Roman ships, and this information constitutes one kind of relation in a broader transportation system.

Edge list and adjacency matrix

In order to produce the network, we create first an edge list object called edgel with the two network variables in sw cleaned with the cln() options showed above.

# clean and remove NA entries
edgel <- sdam::cln(sw[ ,20:21], level=2, what=c("(",")"), case=1, na.rm=TRUE)
# head and tail of edge list
rbind(head(edgel), tail(edgel))
                   Place of origin      Place of destination
1                            Egypt            Northern Italy
2                              Cos            Northern Italy
3                           Rhodes            Northern Italy
4                           Aegean            Northern Italy
6                           Rhodes            Northern Italy
7                           Aegean            Northern Italy
1740             Herakleia Pontica                    Bizone
1754                       Baetica                      Rome
1755                     Lusitania                      Rome
1756 Southern Spain Via Marseilles                      Pisa
1759     Southern Levant Or Cyprus Southern Levant Or Cyprus
1765         Central Western Italy                    Aegean

The code below uses function read.srt() from package "multiplex" to transform the edge list into the adjacency matrix of the network in object mat where the edge list then

# construct matrix from edge list assuming one relation
mat <- multiplex::read.srt(edgel)
# size of matrix
dim(mat)
[1] 143 143

Graph representations

Then we plot the Roman Shipwrecks network as a directed graph using a layout algorithm with package "multigraph", and with the force-directed layout of the graph, it is easy to see network components.

Graph for Strauss Roman Shipwrecks network. 

# plot customized graph
multigraph(mat, coord=cdsmat, pos=0, ecol=4, col=8, vcol0=7, rot=55, vedist=5, alpha=c(1,.5))

There may be other records like that one and some of the dyadic components are indeed part of the largest component of the Roman Shipwrecks network; however, the rest of the adjustments needs to be by hand by or in coordination with a domain expert.

Function comps() from package "multiplex" provides the network components and isolates with the relations recorded in the adjacency matrix in mat.

By selecting the largest component with argument 'sel' in function rel.sys(), we obtain the adjacency matrix as an array 'type' object that is recorded in matc.

# adjacency matrix of selected largest component
matc <- multiplex::rel.sys(mat, type="toarray", sel=comps(mat)$com[[2]])
# matrix size
dim(matc)
[1] 95 95

Then plot the largest component in the Roman Shipwrecks network where locations and their connections are easier to see.

Largest component in Roman Shipwrecks network. 

# graph of largest component with adjusted vertex-edge distance
multigraph(matc, coord=cdsmatc, pos=0, ecol=4, col=8, vcol0=7, hds=.2, vedist=-6, alpha=c(1,.5))

Seas in Mediterranean Basin

All locations in the two network variables, Place of origin and Place of destination, belong to a certain sea or region in the Mediterranean Basin or neighboring waters. One could use information from the Sea area variable in sw; however, this variable corresponds to the shipwreck locations, which in many cases are far from the origin and destination of the ship.

The following characters serve to discern clusters of origin and destination places within Strauss Roman Shipwrecks network where most sea names are in D. Hessong cartographical map (2001).

  • A or : Aegean, including Minoan Sea
  • D: Adriatic Sea
  • I: Ionian Sea, including Ausonian Sean and Messenian Sea
  • T: Tyrrhenian Sea
  • B: Baetica, including Alboran/Iberian Sea
  • L: Ligurian Sea, including Baleares
  • E: East, from Cilician Strait through Levante Basin
  • F: Africa, including Libyan Sea and Cyrene
  • P: Punic Sea, including Berber Sea
  • C: Black Sea
  • G: Gaul
  • X: India

Because some locations entries in this dataset are vague, the clustering information for the places of origin and destination for the reduction of the network result ambiguous with entries having more than one letter.

The assignation of sea regions to the places of origin and destination was made by hand and are recorded in a tabular separated table in file ShipwreckSeas.txt. To load this file into object ss we need to specify the separator of the data that in this case has a header.

# read file with Mediterranean sea regions per place
ss <- read.table(file="ShipwreckSeas.txt", header=TRUE, sep="\t")

An excerpt of ss given below illustrates the location ambiguity in the data. For instance, Aegean And Italy in entry 8 imply three possible region seas that are Aegean, Ionian, and Adriatic; however, Aegean Rome in entry 10 implies the west coast of the Italian peninsula. In this case, the sea region includes the Tyrrhenian Sea rather than the east coast facing the Adriatic.

# excerpt with 9 sea regions
ss[8:16,]
                        PLACE  CODE
8            Aegean And Italy A,D,I
9    Aegean And Lastly Cyprus   A,E
10                Aegean Rome A,T,I
11  Aegean Tripolitania Italy A,D,I
12            Aegean Via Cosa     A
13  Aegean Via Southern Italy   A,I
14              Aegean, Italy A,D,I
15              Aegean/Africa   A,F
16 Aegean/N. Africa/Propontis   A,F

Network reduction

A clustering information serves to reduce the network into related sets of equivalent places in the system.

# matching sea regions to the edge list
ss[c(head(match(edgel[,1], ss$PLACE),3), tail(match(edgel[,1], ss$PLACE),3)),]
                            PLACE CODE
73                          Egypt    E
60                            Cos    A
137                        Rhodes    A
153 Southern Spain Via Marseilles    B
152     Southern Levant Or Cyprus    E
53          Central Western Italy    T

Then we create a data frame edgelc with the codes in ss.

# data frame with codes
edgelc <- cbind(edgel, from=ss[match(edgel[,1], ss$PLACE),]$CODE, 
                       to=ss[match(edgel[,2], ss$PLACE),]$CODE)

and look at the head of the data frame

head(edgelc)

The adjacency matrix of letters in mat0 comes from columns from and to in edgelc

# beta version function
mat0 <- read.srt(edgelc[,3:4])

and then plot the multigraph of the reduced structure.

# list of characteristics
scp <- list(pos=0, ecol=4, col=8, vcol0=7, cex=3)
# plot multigraph
multigraph(mat0, valued=TRUE, scope=scp, layout="force", seed=123, alpha=c(1,.5))

Sea regions in the Roman Shipwrecks network as valued graph.

There are 50 asymmetric ties in the Roman Shipwrecks network and the Aegean Sea has the most reciprocated ties in this system. Letter R in the summary of the bundles output represents maritime routes relations.
